HANDLING, RESTRAINT
🩺
🩺
GENERALITIES
-> Animals can
- Strike with forelimbs
- Kick with hindlimbs
- Bite
- Step on someone’s feet
- Squeeze handlers against walls
- Jump on top of a person
- Zoonotic potential
=> All these actions can inflict injuries ranging from mild to serious and crippling
+ Male aggression
- Males will fight other males or people to establish dominance
- Castrate any males not intended for breeding (especially horses and farm animals)

GENERAL RULES

HANDLING AND RESTRAINT OF PIGS

- The animal should be carefully observed and we should try to establish friendly contact
- We try to be calm but determined and confident at the same time
- Application of restrictive procedures from mild to…..
-> Speak softly with a low tone of voice when working around animals
- Yelling may result in an animal becoming fearful, and attempting to kick, charge, or run
- Animals can detect noises that humans cannot hear
-> Animals have excellent memories
- Painful or aversive experiences may result in reluctance to be handled subsequent times
- Abused animals can be very dangerous

HANDLING AND RESTRAINT OF CATS

- The major weapon of the pig is the teeth -> The boar has long canine teeth (tusks) which can inflict serious injury
- Animals should be de-tusked
- Sow with a litter may attack a person and bite
- Both boars and sows are unpredictable and may attack without warning
- It is difficult to capture or handle an adult pig in a large enclosure
-> necessary to move them into a smaller pen where movement is restricted
- We can use a hog board - a portable wall to coax or trap pig in a desired area
- A pig up to 50 kg can be restrained by a person standing astride it, with a leg against each shoulder, and holding on to its ears
- An older pig generally is restrained using a nose snare or snubbing rope, placed around the upper jaw behind the canine teeth
- Piglets may be held in the hands with one hand under the chest and the other over the back between the shoulders
=> Never grab piglets from the ears or the tail !
-> They should be caught by the hind legs, picked up gently and held between the hands

+ Maternal aggression
- Animals can be very protective and defensive of their young
- Be alert to warning signals

-> Dogs behavior is determined by:
- Breed
- Age
- Training
- Genetic: breeds with excitable temperaments are more likely to be difficult to handle in a new surrounding
- Previous experience and degree of human contact
-> Dog body language:
- Playful
- Alert and attentive
⚠ Never put your face directly into the face of a dog or cat
- Concentrate on the dog you are handling without being distracted by other activities
- NEVER sit on the floor while handling/examining a dog ( you have to be able to move away if dog becomes unexpectedly aggressive)
-> Socialize with a dog
- Call the dog by name and encourage the dog to come to you
- If the dog doesn't come, slowly approach from the front
- Never surprise the animal by approaching from behind
- Extend your hand, palm down
- Let the animal sniff your hand, then slowly move your hand to touch the side of the face then stroke the top of the head
-> Restraint on the table
- Dogs always should be held on the table
- Never left unattended
- Lifting the dog on the table: the owner lifts the front part of the body and the assistant back part
-> Standing Restraint for Dogs
- One arm is under the dog’s neck
- Other arm is behind the rear legs or under dog’s abdomen
⚠ If the owner is holding the dog, don’t take the pet from their arms (dogs may be protective to their owners and may bite if they feel you
are threatening their owner)
-> Muzzle
- Choose the right size of muzzle
- Do not apply a muzzle in dogs that are difficult to breathe or vomit
- The muzzle should not be on dog for long periods of time
- Do not leave muzzled dog unattended
-> Elizabethan collars
- These plastic collars prevent the dog from licking or chewing at wounds, bandages or sutures on the body or legs
- They may also be used to keep the animal from biting the handler
-> Chemical restraint : several different analgesics, tranquilizers and sedatives are available
- Acepromazine - sedation
- Diazepam -mild sedation
- Oxymorphone –sedation, analgesia
- Butorphanol – analgesia, mild sedation

HANDLING AND RESTRAINT OF SHEEP AND GOATS
=> Sheep and goats are one of the easiest domestic animals to restrain for clinical examaination
-> Tipping Sheep
- Putting sheep in a position to check its mouth, eyes, feet, etc.
- Hold the animal by the neck and the rump from the left side
- Place the right knee in the left flank of animal
- Grasp the right flank with right hand
- The animal ̍ s head and neck are then twisted to the right with left hand
- At the same time the handler’s knee is pressed into the right flank and the sheep is whirled around and set down
CLINICAL TIP
Never grab sheeps by their whool !!! It is as sensitive as our hairs - Take one of their hinlimbs to
guide them where you want, the 3 other limbs will follow to maintain the balance of the body

-> Restraint on the table
(+ Scruff on the neck)

Avoid doing it with patients that are not used to it !

-> Chemical restraint
- Diazepam
- Midazolam
- Acepromazine
- Ketamine

-> Handling the animal is always stressful condition and should be minimized whenever possible
- Various types of animals have different methods of restraint
- Animals behave differently in their own and in an unknown space
- There are differences in temperament and upbringing

-> Handling and Restraint of dogs for Clinical Examination depend on:
- The dog's behavior
- Clinician aproach
- Environment
- Degree of discomfort caused by examination

- Cat body language
- Cats are usually transported in carriers or baskets
- The windows and doors should be closed before opening the cats carrier
- The owner may be better to coax a cat out of its cage and restrain it
-> A non-aggressive cat will usually come out of the cage on its own
+ if approached calmly & will allow examination

-> Elizabethan collars

-> Restraint has been defined as the restriction of an animal’s activity by:
1. Non contact: (Voice, eye contact, gesture)
2. Manual or physical: (Using body or devices)
3. Chemical: (Using tranquilizers or anesthetics)
4. Combination methods: (Using two or more of the previous methods)
-> The use of proper restraint and handling techniques reduces stress to animals and also to the clinician

HANDLING AND RESTRAINT OF DOGS

=> Of all domestic animals, the cat is one of the most unpredictable and difficult to handle and restraint
- They defend themselves by biting and scratching
- Cats have retractable claws
- They can with scratching inflict Cat scratch disease in humans

HANDLING AND RESTRAINT OF CATTLE
-> Basic safety principles
- Wear sturdy, closed-toe shoes
- Speak softly and kindly when approaching an animal
- Use adequate restraining and handling facilities when working with animals
- Always leave yourself an escape route when working with animals
- Do not handle livestock when you are alone
- Herd animals often become agitated and fearful when animal is separated from the herd
- Animals will make every effort to return to the herd

-> Horses vary in size from miniature horses (pony) which may weigh only 50 kg to large draft, horses weighing up to 1200-1400 kg

- Dairy cows are mostly calm and stable animals and we usually can perform clinical examination without problems
- They are also like other herbivorous easy startled so our approach have to be calm and gentle but careful (they are big animals weighted about 400 kg)
- Cows which have horns can suddenly attack with horns both forward and sideways
- Handler working around the head of horned animal must be continually conscious of the swinging arc of the head and the extent of the reach of the horns
- Horned and dehorned cattle may head butt
- They may rush at people and knock them down
- May also push against people with their bodies, squeezing them against walls, fences or other animals
- Cows rarely kick with hindlimbs backward and usually kick only with one leg at the time in contrast to the horse where both hindlimbs habitually kick simultaneously
- More often kicks with hindlimbs toward side
- Cattle seldom use the front feet as weapons, though they may paw the ground to display anger
- They can step on someone’s feet
-> Cattle have almost 300 degrees of vision
- This is typical of prey species
- This is in contrast to predators that have eyes on the front of their head
- Cattle frighten easily if handlers suddenly enter their field of vision without warning

It is completely safe to stand directly behind the cow. However, you should never stand
alongside the hind leg, because if the cow kicks with its back legs, the kick will be
directed laterally.

-> Cattle on the pasture:
- We observe all herd and if we have to examine one animal we have to separate it and perform examination in some quite place where we can tie and fix the animal
- On big farms cattle can be fixed with stanchion on feeding table
- In overcrowded stables we should be careful because the other animals can squeeze or kick us
- In most cases we will be able to do a clinical examination without any problems
- Cows are mostly very calm in the case of rectal examination
-> Halter
- A rope halter is the basic tool of restraining for cattle
- It is standard practice to place the halter on the animal on the left side
- Halter provides secure way to leading the cattle

HANDLING AND RESTRAINT OF HORSE

CLINICAL TIP
In our basic position, we stand laterally beside the cow, midway between the front
legs and the hind legs. We turn toward the rear if we need to work on the back
part of the cow, and we turn toward the front if we need to work on the front part.
We try to keep one hand in constant contact with the top of the spine so that we
can push the cow away from us immediately in case of danger. We also keep a
safe distance whenever possible and make sure that we are always able to move
away quickly and free ourselves from the cow if necessary.

+ Horned cattle can be restrained by holding both horns or tying them to a strong post
-> Cows have an unusually sensitive nasal septum
- Routine restraint practice is to grasp this between the thumb and finger via nostrils, forming a manual nose tong
-> Is very hard to maintain sufficient pressure for more then a few second
- Comercially available nose tongs (cattle leader, bull nose holder)
-> When fully closed, a space of approximately 3,5 mm should remain between the two balls to prevent necrosis of the nasal cartilage
-> An assistant must hold the tongs, or rope can be tied above and to the side of the stanchion or chute
-> To prevent kicking with the hind leg
- The assistant can grasp, lift and hold the skin above the knee
- The commercial device for the same purpose :
-> Stock
-> Crush : cattle crush is a strongly built cage for holding cattles safely
- The rearlimbs are tied with metal hobble (or rope hobble) to prevent kicking (especially during milking)
-> Tail-jack
- Restraint the tail: to reduce the movement of tail we can tie tail with rope on one leg
- This device is applied on the base of the tail to prevent tail movement and possible slaping the ordinarius

- The horse can kick backwards with one or both hindlimbs
- The horses can strike forward with the forelimbs with absolutely no warning
-> It is not recommended to stand directly in front of the horse
- Horses also can seriously bite, they can fracture the bones in the hand of a mature person
- For examination of the halter-trained horse it may be sufficient to have the owner the hold the horse with a lead shank attached to the halter
- The safiest place for handler is to stand next to the left forelimb
- It is recommended to stand close to the horse body to prevent kicking, striking and biting
- Continually speaking to the horse and calling it by name prevent frightening and consequent kicking
- When we get to the horse we grab and hold it for the halter
- Leading the horse from the stable holding the rope attached to halter
- When administering medicines by injection or blood sampling we can distract the horse attention with grasping the skin on the neck
-> Twich – distracts the animal attention away from the clinician and the part of the body during examination
- When we putting the twich we first grab the upper lip and spread with fingers the loop
- Place the loop over the upper lip with one hand, while the other twists the handle so that the lip is twisted into a firm grasp but not
painfully tight
- Once the lip twich is applied, the assistant holds the twitch and halter at the same time
+ We can apply twicth on the ear
+ To distract the animal‘s attention away from the clinician and the part of the body being examined especially the legs, the assistant can rise the
forelimb
-> Clinician's position during auscultation of the heart
- High binding prevents kicking with hindlimbs
-> Stock
- Restraint device or chute for horses, constructed of wood or metal
- Diagnostic techniques such as rectal examination, passage of nasogastric tube, dental examination etc. are commonly performed with the
animal in stock
- The stock has front and rear openings
> Horse is cross-tied and that prevents sudden jumping and moving forward
- In stock we can easily perform clinical examination of all parts of horse body
- The side wall can also be opened
- On market and in use there are many types of stocks
- Breeding hobbles: are commonly used in the hand breeding of horses to prevent the mare from kicking the stallion
- Cradles : collar that prevents the horse from licking or chewing a wound or a bandage on the body or limbs
- Cross-tie
-> Prevents the horse from licking or chewing wound or a bandage on the limbs or body
-> It is also useful in transporting the animals
- Blindfolds
-> Are useful in loading a shy horse into a vehicle, stall or enclosure that it is afraid to enter
-> The horse must be under the complete control of an experienced handler when the blindfold is placed
- A basket that prevents taking the food
-> Handling and restraint of foals
- We always examine the foals in the presence of it’s mother
- Foal is usually easy to restrain by simply grasping the tail with one hand and the neck with the other hand and arm
- Slings : are used to assist the recumbent horse to its feet or to give a weak animal some assistance or support while standing
> They are not suitable for use with animals that cannot bear their full body weight on the limbs once standing
-> Chemical restraint
- Detomidine
- Xylazine
- Butorpfanol
- Morfine
- Acepromazine

Recumbent horse lies on the weak side and turn to get up on their strong side

-> Restraint the calf
-> Dairy and beef bulls are extremely dangerous and special restraint practices must be observed when working with them
- All bulls should be handled with care and caution
- Ideally, every mature bull should have a nose ring
⚠ Never trust the bull !!!
- Manipulating with bull demands experienced handler and using an excellent chutes (crush)
-> Coaxing and assisting recumbent cattle to stand
- If animals are able to stand but need some coaxing we can stimulate them to stand with slight jolt with an electric prod
- If animals are unable to stand, it may be necesssary to provide assistance with hip lifters or slings
> The hip lifters (clamps) are applied across both tuber coxae which provides lifting points
> Considerable tissue damage below the tuber coxae can occur if clamps are not used carefully
- A simple and inexpensive way to lift cows is with cow lifter
> Developed for the medium term support (up to four hours) of weak and down cows
-> Chemical restraint
- Acepromazine
- Xylazine
- Butorphanol
- Detomidine
- Chloral hydrate

